              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7436362238175424216">Apparently I&apos;m a Stoic always was one. That&apos;s about all I picked up from this book. I thought to myself &quot;what better way to learn more about Stoicism than to read from the original texts.&quot; Well that was an error. All I get is a long rambling collection of letters. Most of the time I&apos;m not entirely sure what Seneca&apos;s point is. Sometimes it&apos;s all to obvious and he doesn&apos;t need to go on and on. But that&apos;s what you get with a collection of letters and not a book. It&apos;s inherent in the structure. Well</span>
  <span id="freeText7436362238175424216" style="display:none">Apparently I'm a Stoic always was one. That's about all I picked up from this book. I thought to myself "what better way to learn more about Stoicism than to read from the original texts." Well that was an error. All I get is a long rambling collection of letters. Most of the time I'm not entirely sure what Seneca's point is. Sometimes it's all to obvious and he doesn't need to go on and on. But that's what you get with a collection of letters and not a book. It's inherent in the structure. Well I guess I'll just stoically accept it for what it is. But from now on I'm going to check out some more modern authors to see if they can present the ideas in a more coherent fashion. </span>
  <a data-text-id="7436362238175424216" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

